{"id":14880750,"mediaExerciseId":"b4592d95-c058-4ee1-adaf-e5dba0e6bb2d","exerciseName":"11","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5905502,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to explain about the enterprise value.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"When a company is acquired, the enterprise value is used because the acquiring firm will have to assume the debt of its targeted purchase. \n\nTheoretically, **enterprise value** is the purchase price or the takeover price. When a company is taken over, the buyer would need to pay the value of the company's debt. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/235fc6065aeb877f5c90027e7ab11043/84c9604c3d73ea8afc38adffcf212bcc/lateximg_large.png","width":827},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/235fc6065aeb877f5c90027e7ab11043/84c9604c3d73ea8afc38adffcf212bcc/lateximg.png","width":414}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"18acad90-d1ed-4370-82a2-c7e294446664","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2},{"id":5979132,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise asks us to explain why enterprise value is relevant information for potential purchases of a business.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/733231a44863ff213d5745d741bb58b4/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":33,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/733231a44863ff213d5745d741bb58b4/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Enterprise value** refers to the amount or price that a potential buyer should pay for acquiring a firm. It equates to the net market value of business liabilities and equity after deducting all cash reserves.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/8f9afc7eaabf17cfb32084f597515ef6/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/8f9afc7eaabf17cfb32084f597515ef6/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Unlike market capitalization, which measures a company's value based on the stock market, enterprise value is essential for a company takeover. The price that a **potential purchaser** should pay for acquiring a business should consider the obligations that would pass through the transaction.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/a854a21ab9c3f3f1ee0d0f4674aa4d22/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/a854a21ab9c3f3f1ee0d0f4674aa4d22/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"In a business takeover, items that will go to the buyer **includes business liabilities**. Considering the value of assets and the related liabilities that a buyer will assume can give a more accurate picture of the firm's net worth or real value.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/54271e10b6e57ddfa5c7dcc101127574/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/b75db3de12448c3d0cfcd5922acb1571/54271e10b6e57ddfa5c7dcc101127574/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"ae83e25d-033d-4f85-9335-8e1e5e77d555","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880751,"exerciseName":"12","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"e318f2f7-abac-4baf-a4ad-865fc03ee609","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-12-e318f2f7-abac-4baf-a4ad-865fc03ee609"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880749,"exerciseName":"10","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"19ee8364-760b-489b-ac16-d492be8a4a08","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-10-19ee8364-760b-489b-ac16-d492be8a4a08"},{"id":14880748,"exerciseName":"9","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaEx